I"•1<h2 id="dollar-cost-averaging-definition">Dollar Cost Averaging Definition</h2>

<blockquote>
  <p>Dollar cost averaging, or DCA for short, means investing certain set amount of money into an asset on a regular basis, disregarding the momentarily price action on the market.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>DCA is a technique that has been strongly recommended by Warren Buffet. He probably wouldn‚Äôt approve of it for cryptocurrencies, though. The reason is, dollar cost averaging is effectively a way to build a position on a market where you have a strong long-term bullish bias. It is easy to see it was an easy low-cost and low-effort way to profit from the ‚Äúeternal growth‚Äù of legacy capital markets.</p>

<h4 id="benefits-of-dca">Benefits of DCA</h4>

<p>The benefits of dollar cost averaging show best in markets that have been slumping or ranging markets for a prolonged period of time when the trading volumes are low.</p>

<p>With low trading participation on the market the predictive powers of technical analysis decrease as well and because it is not a problem anymore to trade cryptocurrencies through legacy institutions with non-retail amounts of money, every market weakness can be hammered into an abrupt run in either direction.</p>

<p>The legacy capital market equivalent would be the comparison of buying physical precious metals, concluding it has good value to do that considering some broader market view, versus for instance leveraged speculation on the silver market where <a href="https://www.ft.com/content/2d7be5a6-d87a-11e9-8f9b-77216ebe1f17">JP Morgan provably held such a big multi-year short position</a> that it was effectively naked.</p>

<h2 id="dollar-cost-averaging-strategy">Dollar Cost Averaging Strategy</h2>

<p>On a superficial glance it may seem as if DCA is a way to avoid making directional decisions for market. That is wrong though: With DCA you are avoiding short- to medium-term directional speculation which can be a very reasonable decision. In some market conditions there simply isn‚Äôt a good enough opportunity to trade on TA.</p>

<p>If you decide to dollar cost average your exposure to an asset, it is indeed a bigger commitment than with a short-term bet, but also a bigger commitment than simple hodling.</p>

<p>Long-term holders without a regular strategy have bought their stash in several (not many) splurges and since then idly follow the price development to see if the price got high enough for them to sell.</p>

<p>Over the span of a decade or two, the difference between ‚Äúhaving a stash‚Äù and DCA amounts to suprisingly much.</p>

<h4 id="how-to-maximize-crypto-dca-benefits">How to Maximize Crypto DCA Benefits</h4>

<p>Let‚Äôs crunch the numbers.</p>

<p><a target="_blank" href="https://res.cloudinary.com/atnetcloud/image/upload/c_lpad,h_360,w_700/v1598344273/atnet/strategy/btcusd-trend_bmzsqo.jpg" title="AltcoinTrading.NET - "><figure class="border"><amp-img itemprop="image" src="https://res.cloudinary.com/atnetcloud/image/upload/c_lpad,h_360,w_700/v1598344273/atnet/strategy/btcusd-trend_bmzsqo.jpg" alt="" title="AltcoinTrading.NET - " layout="responsive" width="700px" height="360px"></amp-img></figure></a></p>

<p>The two tables below show the net worth for an investor who bought up a stash of 10, 50 or 200 BTC at 10k or under. You see how the value of the stash rises if BTC appreciates to 50k USD or more.</p>

<p>I would argue that 50k is a reasonable and quite conservative target within the next bull cycle, 100k would surprise me and I find it unlikely to happen in the next 5-10 years. It is included for those hodlers often do their math starting from how much they want their stash to be worth one day.</p>

<p>In these conditions, if you started with a stash of 10 BTC only, you have a chance of hitting 1 MM USD at best.</p>

