<h2 id="dollar-cost-averaging-bitcoin-and-other-crypto">Dollar Cost Averaging Bitcoin and Other Crypto</h2>

<p>To reiterate what we just did in the pervious section: Cryptocurrencies have the potential to increase in value greatly over the years, but please keep it real - nothing is guaranteed.</p>

<p>Even if your reasons to DCA in bitcoin are solid, I think it is still about finding the right balance. If you look at it as money for personal use only, at some point the differences will start to lose meaning.</p>

<p>You won‚Äôt able to spend it all and if you leave it to kids you might as well consider the money lost. I don‚Äôt think it warrants living extremely frugally for 20 years in order to die with 6 millions instead of 4 millions. But as always, you do you.</p>

<h2 id="methods-related-to-dca">Methods related to DCA</h2>

<p>Lastly, it is worth mentioning an alternative strategy that sounds similar to DCA and could appeal to investors who tend to avoid risks. It is called Value Cost Averaging and while on surface it might look rational and reasonable, it does not actually make much sense in principle.</p>

<p>With Value Cost Averaging the investor makes regular purchases of an asset just like with DCA, but instead of the invested amount the value of the purchase asset is set. The point of VCA is to avoid unnecessarily high exposure to an asset that might have gotten ahead of itself in terms of its valuation. If you see you have been decreasing your stake every round of buying, it is essentially the signal for you to exit your position on someone else before the crashes never to recover.</p>

<p>It might be reasonable on the legacy markets, especially when you consider questionable areas like tech unicorn valuations. In cryptocurrency markets, higher volatility is the norm. Cryptocurrencies die but within the next month they might be already recovering. Other than for stablecoins, huge price level differences year-on-year are still to be expected for some time. What VCA will do for you on this kind of market is progressively decrease your exposure to an asset that is gaining you the most money.</p>

<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>

<p>Dollar cost averaging in crypto is a method to progressively build an unleveraged position in your cryptoasset of choice. It is a good fit for you if you have a regular income and a bullish outlook on crypto for the long-term horizon.</p>

<p>Dollar cost averaging is a particularly good fit for you if you tick the previous two points plus you don‚Äôt currently have a massive long-term stash yet.</p>

<p>It might seem it is too late to invest, but monthly contributions over long period of time do add up.</p>
